1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ENACT IRYNA'S LAW; TO MODIFY THE LAW RELATED TO PRETRIAL
3 RELEASE CONDITIONS; TO ADD AN AGGRAVATING SENTENCING FACTOR; TO
4 MODIFY SUSPENSION OF MAGISTRATES; TO DIRECT THE COLLABORATORY
5 TO STUDY MENTAL HEALTH AND THE JUSTICE SYSTEM; TO PROHIBIT
6 CERTAIN TASK FORCES; TO MODIFY DEATH PENALTY PROCEEDINGS; TO
7 MODIFY THE PROCEDURES FOR INVOLUNTARY COMMITMENT OF A
8 DEFENDANT FOUND INCAPABLE OF PROCEEDING; TO EXTEND TERMS OF
9 PROBATION AND POST-RELEASE SUPERVISION FOR YOUTH ADJUDICATED OF
10 CERTAIN VIOLENT OFFENSES AND TO CLARIFY A VICTIM'S RIGHT TO BE
11 NOTIFIED ABOUT TERMINATION OF PROBATION OR POST-RELEASE
12 SUPERVISION; AND TO APPROPRIATE FUNDS FOR ADDITIONAL ASSISTANT
13 DISTRICT ATTORNEYS AND LEGAL ASSISTANTS IN JUDICIAL DISTRICT 26 AND
14 TO REQUIRE CERTAIN INVOLUNTARY COMMITMENT RESPONDENTS TO
15 REMAIN IN CUSTODY PENDING HEARING.
16 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
17
18 MODIFY THE LAW RELATED TO PRETRIAL RELEASE CONDITIONS
19 SECTION 1.(a) G.S. 15A-501 reads as rewritten:
20 "§ 15A-501. Police processing and duties upon arrest generally.
21 Upon the arrest of a person, with or without a warrant, but not necessarily in the order
22 hereinafter listed, a law-enforcement officer:
23 (1) Must inform the person arrested of the charge against him or the cause for his
24 arrest.
25 (2) Must, with respect to any person arrested without a warrant and, for purpose
26 of setting bail, with respect to any person arrested upon a warrant or order for
27 arrest, take the person arrested before a judicial official without unnecessary
28 delay.
29 (2a) Must inform any judicial official determining conditions of pretrial release
30 pursuant to Article 26 of this Chapter of any relevant behavior of the defendant
31 observed by the officer prior to, during, or after the arrest that may provide
32 reasonable grounds for the judicial official to believe the defendant is a danger
33 to themselves or others.
*H307-v-4*

