31 SECTION 1.(c) G.S. 15A-533 reads as rewritten:
32 "§ 15A-533. Right to pretrial release in capital and noncapital cases.
33 (a) A defendant charged with any crime, whether capital or noncapital, who is alleged to
34 have committed this crime while still residing in or subsequent to his escape or during an
35 unauthorized absence from involuntary commitment in a mental health facility designated or
36 licensed by the Department of Health and Human Services, and whose commitment is determined
37 to be still valid by the judge or judicial officer authorized to determine pretrial release to be valid,
38 has no right to pretrial release. In lieu of pretrial release, however, the individual shall be returned
39 to the treatment facility in which he was residing at the time of the alleged crime or from which
40 he escaped or absented himself for continuation of his treatment pending the additional
41 proceedings on the criminal offense.
42 (b) A judge shall determine in the judge's discretion whether a defendant charged with
43 any of the following crimes may be released before trial:
44 (1) G.S. 14-17 (First or second degree murder) or an attempt to commit first or
45 second degree murder.
46 (2) G.S. 14-27.21 (First degree forcible rape).
47 (3) G.S. 14-27.22 (Second degree forcible rape).
48 (4) G.S. 14-27.23 (Statutory rape of a child by an adult).
49 (5) G.S. 14-27.24 (First degree statutory rape).
50 (6) G.S. 14-27.25 (Statutory rape of person who is 15 years of age or younger).
51 (7) G.S. 14-27.26 (First degree forcible sexual offense).
