26 A defendant may be retained in custody pursuant to this subsection not more than 48 hours
27 from the time of arrest without a judge making a determination of conditions of pretrial release.
28 If a judge has not acted pursuant to this subsection within 48 hours from the time of arrest of the
29 defendant, the magistrate shall set conditions of pretrial release in accordance with
30 G.S. 15A-534."
31 SECTION 1.(d) G.S. 15A-534 reads as rewritten:
32 "§ 15A-534. Procedure for determining conditions of pretrial release.
33 (a) In determining conditions of pretrial release a judicial official must impose at least
34 one of the following conditions:
35 (1) Release the defendant on his written promise to appear.
36 (2) Release the defendant upon his execution of an unsecured appearance bond in
37 an amount specified by the judicial official.
38 (3) Place the defendant in the custody of a designated person or organization
39 agreeing to supervise him.
40 (4) Require the execution of an appearance bond in a specified amount secured
41 by a cash deposit of the full amount of the bond, by a mortgage pursuant to
42 G.S. 58-74-5, or by at least one solvent surety.
43 (5) House arrest with electronic monitoring.
44 If condition (5) is imposed, the defendant must execute a secured appearance bond under
45 subdivision (4) of this subsection. If condition (3) is imposed, however, the defendant may elect
46 to execute an appearance bond under subdivision (4). If the defendant is required to provide
47 fingerprints pursuant to G.S. 15A-502(a1), (a2), (a4), or (a6), or a DNA sample pursuant to
48 G.S. 15A-266.3A or G.S. 15A-266.4, and (i) the fingerprints or DNA sample have not yet been
49 taken or (ii) the defendant has refused to provide the fingerprints or DNA sample, the judicial
50 official shall make the collection of the fingerprints or DNA sample a condition of pretrial
51 release. The judicial official may also place restrictions on the travel, associations, conduct, or
House Bill 307-Fourth Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 place of abode of the defendant as conditions of pretrial release. The judicial official may include
2 as a condition of pretrial release that the defendant abstain from alcohol consumption, as verified
3 by the use of a continuous alcohol monitoring system, of a type approved by the Division of
4 Community Supervision and Reentry of the Department of Adult Correction, and that any
5 violation of this condition be reported by the monitoring provider to the district attorney.
6 (b) The Except for a defendant charged with a violent offense, a judicial official in
7 granting pretrial release must impose condition (1), (2), (2) or (3) in subsection (a) above unless
8 he determines that such release will not reasonably assure the appearance of the defendant as
9 required; will pose a danger of injury to any person; or is likely to result in destruction of
10 evidence, subornation of perjury, or intimidation of potential witnesses. Upon making the
11 determination, the judicial official must then impose condition (4) or (5) in subsection (a) above
12 instead of condition (1), (2), (2) or (3), and must record the reasons for so doing in writing to the
13 extent provided in the policies or requirements issued by the senior resident superior court judge
14 pursuant to G.S. 15A-535(a). However, if a defendant has been convicted of three or more
15 offenses, each of which is a Class 1 misdemeanor or higher offense, within the previous 10 years,
16 the judicial official must then impose condition (4) or (5) in subsection (a) of this section.
17 (b1) For a defendant charged with any violent offense, there shall be a rebuttable
18 presumption that no condition of release will reasonably assure the appearance of the person as
19 required and the safety of the community. However, if the judicial official determines that pretrial
20 release is appropriate for a defendant, the judicial official must do one of the following:
21 (1) For a defendant charged with a first violent offense, impose condition (4) or
22 (5) in subsection (a) of this section.
23 (2) For a defendant charged with a second or subsequent violent offense, after (i)
24 being convicted of a prior violent offense, or (ii) being released on pretrial
25 release conditions for a prior violent offense, impose condition (5) in
26 subsection (a) of this section, if available.
27 (c) In determining which conditions of release to impose, the judicial official shall direct
28 the arresting law enforcement officer, a pretrial services program, or a district attorney to provide
29 a criminal history report for the defendant and shall consider the criminal history when setting
30 conditions of pretrial release. Additionally, the judicial official must, on the basis of available
31 information, take into account the nature and circumstances of the offense charged; the weight
32 of the evidence against the defendant; the defendant's family ties, employment, financial
33 resources, character, housing situation, and mental condition; whether the defendant is
34 intoxicated to such a degree that he would be endangered by being released without supervision;
35 the length of his residence in the community; his record of convictions; his history of flight to
36 avoid prosecution or failure to appear at court proceedings; and any other evidence relevant to
37 the issue of pretrial release.
38 (d) The judicial official authorizing pretrial release under this section must issue an
39 appropriate order containing a statement of the conditions imposed, if any; inform the defendant
40 in writing of the penalties applicable to violations of the conditions of his release; and advise him
41 that his arrest will be ordered immediately upon any violation. In each and every order
42 authorizing pretrial release for (i) a defendant who is charged with a violent offense or (ii) a
43 defendant who has been convicted of three or more offenses in separate sessions of court, each
44 of which is a Class 1 misdemeanor or higher offense, within the previous 10 years, the judicial
45 official must make written findings of fact explaining the reasons why the judicial official
46 determined the conditions of release to be appropriate by applying the factors provided in
47 subsection (c) of this section. The order of release must be filed with the clerk and a copy given
48 the defendant and any surety, or the agent thereof who is executing the bond for the defendant's
49 release pursuant to that order.
50 (d1) When Except for a defendant charged with a violent offense, when conditions of
51 pretrial release are being imposed on a defendant who has failed on one or more prior occasions
