21 (e) A magistrate or a clerk may modify his pretrial release order at any time prior to the
22 first appearance before the district court judge. At or after such first appearance, except when the
23 conditions of pretrial release have been reviewed by the superior court pursuant to G.S. 15A-539,
24 a district court judge may modify a pretrial release order of the magistrate or clerk or any pretrial
25 release order entered by him at any time prior to:
26 (1) In a misdemeanor case tried in the district court, the noting of an appeal; and
27 (2) In a case in the original trial jurisdiction of the superior court, the binding of
28 the defendant over to superior court after the holding, or waiver, of a
29 probable-cause hearing.
30 After a case is before the superior court, a superior court judge may modify the pretrial release
31 order of a magistrate, clerk, or district court judge, or any such order entered by him, at any time
32 prior to the time set out in G.S. 15A-536(a).
33 (f) For good cause shown any judge may at any time revoke an order of pretrial release.
34 Upon application of any defendant whose order of pretrial release has been revoked, the judge
35 must set new conditions of pretrial release in accordance with this Article.
36 (g) In imposing conditions of pretrial release and in modifying and revoking orders of
37 release under this section, the judicial official must take into account all evidence available to
38 him which he considers reliable and is not strictly bound by the rules of evidence applicable to
39 criminal trials.
40 (h) A bail bond posted pursuant to this section is effective and binding upon the obligor
41 throughout all stages of the proceeding in the trial division of the General Court of Justice until
42 the entry of judgment in the district court from which no appeal is taken or the entry of judgment
