25 SECTION 7.(a) G.S. 15A-1003 reads as rewritten:
26 "§ 15A-1003. Referral of incapable defendant for civil commitment proceedings.
27 (a) When a defendant is found to be incapable of proceeding, the presiding judge, upon
28 such additional hearing, if any, as he determines to be necessary, shall determine whether there
29 are reasonable grounds to believe the defendant meets the criteria for involuntary commitment
30 under Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes. If the presiding judge finds
31 reasonable grounds to believe that the defendant meets the criteria, he shall make findings of fact
32 and issue a custody order in the same manner, upon the same grounds and with the same effect
33 as an order issued by a clerk or magistrate pursuant to G.S. 122C-261. Proceedings thereafter are
34 in accordance with Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter 122C of the General Statutes. If the defendant
35 was charged with a violent crime, including a crime involving assault with a deadly weapon, the
36 judge's custody order shall require a law-enforcement officer to take the defendant directly to a
37 24-hour facility as described in G.S. 122C-252; and the order must indicate that the defendant
38 was charged with a violent crime and that he was found incapable of proceeding.
39 (a1) Prior to the dismissal of any charges pursuant to G.S. 15A-1008, if the defendant is
40 not subject to an involuntary commitment order issued pursuant to Part 7 of Article 5 of Chapter
41 122C of the General Statutes, the court shall make the determinations and findings required by
42 subsection (a) of this section upon motion of the district attorney.
43 (b) The court may make appropriate orders for the temporary detention of the defendant
44 pending that proceeding.
45 (c) Evidence used at the hearing with regard to capacity to proceed is admissible in the
46 involuntary civil commitment proceedings."
