11 expiration of an order of probation, the court may extend it for an additional period of one year
12 after notice and a hearing, if the court finds that the extension is necessary to protect the
13 community or to safeguard the welfare of the juvenile. At the discretion of the court, the hearing
14 to determine to extend probation may occur after the expiration of an order of probation at the
15 next regularly scheduled court date or if the juvenile fails to appear in court.
16 (c1) Prior to expiration of an order of probation entered for an adjudication of an offense
17 that would be a Class A, B1, or B2 felony if committed by an adult, the court may extend the
18 term of probation for additional periods of up to one year after notice and a hearing, if the court
19 finds that the extension is necessary to protect the community or to safeguard the welfare of the
20 juvenile. The total period of probation entered for an adjudication of an offense that would be a
21 Class A, B1, or B2 felony if committed by an adult shall not exceed three years. At the discretion
22 of the court, the hearing to determine to extend probation may occur after the expiration of an
23 order of probation at the next regularly scheduled court date or if the juvenile fails to appear in
24 court.
25 (d) On motion of the juvenile court counselor or counselor, the juvenile, the prosecutor,
26 or on the court's own motion, the court may review the progress of any juvenile on probation at
27 any time during the period of probation or at the end of probation. The conditions or duration of
28 probation may be modified only as provided in this Subchapter and only after notice and a
29 hearing.
30 …."
31 SECTION 8.(b) G.S. 7B-2511 reads as rewritten:
32 "§ 7B-2511. Termination of probation.
33 At the end of or at any time during probation, the court may terminate probation by written
34 order upon finding that there is no further need for supervision. The Except for cases that involve
35 a victim as defined in Article 20A of this Chapter, the finding and order terminating probation
36 may be entered in chambers in the absence of the juvenile and may be based on a report from the
37 juvenile court counselor or, at the election of the court, the order may be entered with the juvenile
38 present after notice and a hearing. In cases involving a victim as defined in Article 20A of this
39 Chapter, the order may be entered with the juvenile present after notice and a hearing. If a victim
40 has requested to be notified of court proceedings pursuant to G.S. 7B-2053, the Division of
41 Juvenile Justice shall provide notice to the victim, and the court shall provide the prosecutor, the
42 victim, or the person who may assert the victim's rights as set forth in Article 20A of this Chapter
43 the opportunity to be heard at the hearing."
44 SECTION 8.(c) G.S. 7B-2514 reads as rewritten:
45 "§ 7B-2514. Post-release supervision planning; release.
46 …
47 (b) The Division shall develop the plan in writing and base the terms on the needs of the
48 juvenile and the protection of the public. Every Except as otherwise provided in subsection (b1)
49 of this section, every plan shall require the juvenile to complete at least 90 days, but not more
50 than one year, of post-release supervision.
Page 18 House Bill 307-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (b1) Every plan developed for an offense that would be a Class A, B1, B2, or C felony if
2 committed by an adult shall require the juvenile to complete three years of post-release
3 supervision. The Division shall develop the plan in writing and base the terms on the needs of
4 the juvenile and the protection of the public.
5 …
6 (g) A juvenile on post-release supervision shall be supervised by a juvenile court
7 counselor. Post-release supervision shall be terminated by order of the court. For plans developed
8 pursuant to subsection (b1) of this section, post-release supervision may be terminated with the
9 juvenile present after notice and a hearing. If a victim has requested to be notified of court
10 proceedings pursuant to G.S. 7B-2053, the Division of Juvenile Justice shall provide notice to
11 the victim, and the court shall provide the prosecutor, the victim, or the person who may assert
12 the victim's rights as set forth in Article 20A of this Chapter the opportunity to be heard at the
13 hearing."
14 SECTION 8.(d) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
15 offenses committed on or after that date.
