42 REQUIRE AUTHORIZATION FOR RELEASE OF VIOLENT INVOLUNTARY
43 COMMITMENT RESPONDENTS PRIOR TO HEARING
44 SECTION 9.5.(a) G.S. 122C-266 reads as rewritten:
45 "§ 122C-266. Inpatient commitment; second examination and treatment pending hearing.
46 (a) Except as provided in subsections (b) (b), (b1), and (e), within 24 hours of arrival at
47 a 24-hour facility described in G.S. 122C-252, the respondent shall be examined by a physician.
48 This physician shall not be the same physician who completed the certificate or examination
49 under the provisions of G.S. 122C-262 or G.S. 122C-263. The examination shall include but is
50 not limited to the assessment specified in G.S. 122C-263(c).
House Bill 307-Fourth Edition Page 19

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) If the physician finds that the respondent is mentally ill and is dangerous to
2 self, as defined by G.S. 122C-3(11)a., or others, as defined by
3 G.S. 122C-3(11)b., the physician shall hold the respondent at the facility
4 pending the district court hearing.
5 (2) If the physician finds that the respondent meets the criteria for outpatient
6 commitment under G.S. 122C-263(d)(1), the physician shall show these
7 findings on the physician's examination report, release the respondent pending
8 the district court hearing, and notify the clerk of superior court of the county
9 where the petition was initiated of these findings. In addition, the examining
10 physician shall show on the examination report the name, address, and
11 telephone number of the proposed outpatient treatment physician or center.
12 The physician shall give the respondent a written notice listing the name,
13 address, and telephone number of the proposed outpatient treatment physician
14 or center and directing the respondent to appear at that address at a specified
15 date and time. The examining physician before the appointment shall notify
16 by telephone and shall send a copy of the notice and the examination report to
17 the proposed outpatient treatment physician or center.
18 (3) If the physician finds that the respondent does not meet the criteria for
19 commitment under either G.S. 122C-263(d)(1) or G.S. 122C-263(d)(2), the
20 physician shall release the respondent and the proceedings shall be terminated.
21 (4) If the respondent is released under subdivisions (2) or (3) of this subsection,
22 the law enforcement officer or other person designated to provide
23 transportation shall return the respondent to the respondent's residence in the
24 originating county or, if requested by the respondent, to another location in
25 the originating county.
26 (a1) The second examination of a respondent required by subsection (a) of this section to
27 determine whether the respondent will be involuntarily committed due to mental illness may be
28 conducted either in the physical face-to-face presence of a physician or utilizing telehealth
29 equipment and procedures, provided that the physician who examines the respondent by means
30 of telehealth is satisfied to a reasonable medical certainty that the determinations made in
31 accordance with subdivisions (a)(1) through (a)(3) of this section would not be different if the
32 examination had been done in the physical presence of the examining physician. An examining
33 physician who is not so satisfied shall note that the examination was not satisfactorily
34 accomplished, and the respondent shall be taken for a face-to-face examination in the physical
35 presence of a physician. As used in this section, "telehealth" means the use of two-way, real-time
36 interactive audio and video where the respondent and commitment examiner can hear and see
37 each other.
38 (b) If the custody order states that the respondent was charged with a violent crime,
39 including a crime involving assault with a deadly weapon, and that he was found incapable of
40 proceeding, the physician shall examine him as set forth in subsection (a) of this section.
41 However, the physician may not release him from the facility until ordered to do so following
42 the district court hearing.
43 (b1) If the custody order states that the respondent has had a conviction for a violent
44 offense, as defined in G.S. 15A-531, within the previous 10 years, and has been subject to a prior
45 order of involuntary commitment within the previous five years, the physician shall examine the
46 respondent as set forth in subsection (a) of this section. However, the physician may not release
47 the respondent from the facility until one of the following criteria are met:
48 (1) The court has ordered the respondent's release following the district court
49 hearing.
50 (2) Both of the following has occurred:
Page 20 House Bill 307-Fourth Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 a. The physician has provided written certification to the court of all of
2 the following:
3 1. The imminent risk has been remitted.
4 2. Any necessary follow-up appointments or medications have
5 been arranged or provided.
6 3. Any necessary safety plan or housing plan is in place.
7 4. Reasonable efforts have been made to contact the next of kin
8 or a designated support person for the respondent.
9 b. A district court judge has issued an order authorizing release prior to
10 the district court hearing.
11 (c) The findings of the physician and the facts on which they are based shall be in writing,
12 in all cases. A copy of the findings shall be sent to the clerk of superior court (i) through the
13 electronic filing system, if the county has implemented a system approved by the Director of the
14 Administrative Office of the Courts, or (ii) by the most reliable and expeditious means otherwise
15 available.
16 (d) Pending the district court hearing, the physician attending the respondent may
17 administer to the respondent reasonable and appropriate medication and treatment that is
18 consistent with accepted medical standards. Except as provided in subsection (b) of this section,
19 if at any time pending the district court hearing, the attending physician determines that the
20 respondent no longer meets the criteria of either G.S. 122C-263(d)(1) or (d)(2), he shall release
21 the respondent and notify the clerk of court and the proceedings shall be terminated.
22 (e) If the 24-hour facility described in G.S. 122C-252 or G.S. 122C-262 is the facility in
23 which the first examination by a physician or eligible psychologist occurred and is the same
24 facility in which the respondent is held, the second examination shall occur not later than the
25 following regular working day."
26 SECTION 9.5.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2027, and applies to
27 custody orders issued on or after that date.
28
29 EFFECTIVE DATE AND SEVERABILITY
30 SECTION 10.(a) If any provision of this act or its application is held invalid, the
31 invalidity does not affect other provisions or applications of this act that can be given effect
32 without the invalid provisions or application and, to this end, the provisions of this act are
33 severable.
34 SECTION 10.(b) Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
35 law.
